TEST;31-MAR-1987 12:37:45.33;U.S. TAX AGENCY INCREASES INTERNATIONAL AUDITS;  The Internal Revenue Service (IRS) said it was stepping up compliance efforts by its international staff to recover some of the billions of dollars lost each year in unpaid taxes.     The agency was shifting emphasis by its international branch to increase compliance by the 47,000 foreign-owned American companies and foreign firms operating in the United States, IRS officials said at a news conference.     The IRS also was taking a closer look at compliance by Americans living abroad and by taxpayers in the United States with income from overseas investments.     Percy Woodard, assistant IRS commissioner, international, denied that the agency was picking on foreign companies, but he said fewer of them pay taxes than comparable U.S. firms.     In some industries, one pct of foreign firms paid U.S. taxes, he said. Other IRS staff said the taxes paid by foreign companies ranged from 16 to 19 pct less than taxes paid by U.S. firms.     If our taxpayers in another country are expected to fulfill their tax-paying responsibilities in that country

